WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:09.000
[upbeat music playing]

00:10.875 --> 00:15.875
Hi. Unlike you, I'm Rob Lowe,
and I love movies.

00:15.958 --> 00:20.750
The fact is, I'd rather be watching
a movie than doing this right now.

00:20.833 --> 00:24.750
But let's pretend I didn't say that
and just enjoy each other's company.

00:25.541 --> 00:28.791
Thousands of movies
are released every year.

00:28.875 --> 00:30.291
That's a lot of stories,

00:30.375 --> 00:32.583
even though
according to screenwriting theory

00:32.666 --> 00:37.125
there are only seven basic plots:
overcoming the monster...

00:37.875 --> 00:39.083
and the other six.

00:40.416 --> 00:43.291
It's little wonder that stock characters,

00:43.375 --> 00:46.875
familiar story beats,
and convenient plot devices

00:46.958 --> 00:48.166
have crept in over time.

00:48.250 --> 00:52.708
Tonight, we celebrate the clichés
that have made cinema what it is today:

00:52.791 --> 00:55.666
struggling for relevance
in the aftermath of a pandemic.

00:56.458 --> 00:59.541
<i>Over the next hour,</i>
<i>we'll be looking at Tinseltown's habit</i>

00:59.625 --> 01:02.708
<i>of using</i>
<i>these handy cinematic tropes in...</i>

01:02.791 --> 01:05.583
Attack of the Hollywood Clichés!

01:05.666 --> 01:08.125
<i>We'll be asking questions like,</i>

01:08.208 --> 01:11.833
<i>"Why do women being chased</i>
<i>by large, scary dinosaurs</i>

01:11.916 --> 01:13.625
<i>have to do it in high heels?"</i>

01:14.250 --> 01:17.000
<i>As we build to some</i>
<i>of my favorite clichés,</i>

01:17.083 --> 01:20.791
<i>we'll be looking at some of the most</i>
<i>dramatic moments in cinema.</i>

01:21.375 --> 01:23.458
<i>Some of the most controversial.</i>

01:23.541 --> 01:26.333
Sister is teaching the mothers
how to wash their children.

01:26.416 --> 01:29.416
[Lowe] <i>How other clichés have been raised</i>
<i>to a form of high art.</i>

01:29.500 --> 01:31.125
[tires screech]

01:31.208 --> 01:33.666
<i>And of course,</i>
<i>how Hollywood deals with sex.</i>

01:35.041 --> 01:36.083
<i>And violence.</i>

01:37.708 --> 01:40.750
And where better to begin
than with a familiar beginning,

01:40.833 --> 01:44.458
from the world of romantic comedy,
it's the meet cute.

01:47.208 --> 01:50.708
<i>That magical moment in movies</i>
<i>when the love begins.</i>

01:50.791 --> 01:53.708
People watch romcoms to get high.

01:53.791 --> 01:57.250
<i>They wanna experience</i>
<i>that first sensation of love</i>

01:57.333 --> 02:00.750
<i>so that when they see those two people</i>
<i>meet for the very first time,</i>

02:00.833 --> 02:03.500
<i>when that moment, that spark,</i>

02:03.583 --> 02:05.583
<i>that chemistry happens,</i>

02:05.666 --> 02:07.541
it feels so real to them

02:07.625 --> 02:09.666
that they have that sensation
in their body.

02:09.750 --> 02:13.625
There's always some funny, contrived
reason why you have the two people

02:13.708 --> 02:15.916
who are gonna fall in love meet,

02:16.000 --> 02:17.500
<i>because it has to be interesting.</i>

02:17.583 --> 02:20.333
<i>They can't meet</i>
<i>the way regular people meet.</i>

02:21.000 --> 02:23.666
-Lady, keep driving.
-[screams] Get out!

02:23.750 --> 02:27.333
Some kind of embarrassing,
comedic, unlikely scenario...

02:28.666 --> 02:30.083
that brings the two together.

02:30.166 --> 02:33.791
I live just over the street.
I have, um, water and soap.

02:33.875 --> 02:35.000
You can get cleaned up.

02:35.083 --> 02:36.958
[Pugh]<i> If that happened in real life,</i>

02:37.041 --> 02:40.208
you would throw
the rest of your juice in their face.

02:40.291 --> 02:42.625
You'd be like, "No, get away from me."

02:42.708 --> 02:45.416
In five minutes,
we can have you spick and span

02:45.500 --> 02:46.875
and back on the street again,

02:46.958 --> 02:49.291
in the non-prostitute sense, obviously.

02:50.250 --> 02:52.375
[Lowe] <i>Whenever two people</i>
<i>fall in love in a film,</i>

02:52.458 --> 02:57.208
<i>whatever the genre, the clichés</i>
<i>of cinematic romance are ever present.</i>

02:57.916 --> 03:03.791
I hate the water,
and I hate being wet, and I hate you!

03:03.875 --> 03:04.958
Good!

03:05.041 --> 03:08.041
They don't like each other,
are engaged or married to someone else.

03:08.125 --> 03:10.000
Jack, I'm engaged.

03:11.208 --> 03:12.666
I'm marrying Cal.

03:12.750 --> 03:17.041
There has to be a struggle
to go through or else it would be boring.

03:17.875 --> 03:19.875
[Lowe] <i>Of course, this being the movies,</i>

03:19.958 --> 03:24.458
<i>male strategies vary from annoying</i>
<i>persistence to outright harassment.</i>

03:25.125 --> 03:27.458
Well, how about this for a coincidence?

03:27.541 --> 03:31.208
A lot of films which are shown
from the male point of view

03:31.291 --> 03:33.625
feature what you would
really call stalking.

03:33.708 --> 03:35.416
You wanna dance with me?

03:35.500 --> 03:36.750
No.

03:36.833 --> 03:37.833
Why not?

03:37.916 --> 03:39.583
Because I don't want to.

03:39.666 --> 03:41.875
-Well, will you go out with me?
-What?

03:42.625 --> 03:44.583
-No!
-No?

03:44.666 --> 03:46.333
-No!
-No?

03:46.416 --> 03:48.708
-Hey, pal, she just told you.
-Why not?

03:48.791 --> 03:52.375
Like in <i>Twilight,</i> when he
climbs up through her window

03:52.458 --> 03:54.708
<i>and says, "I like watching you sleep."</i>

03:54.791 --> 03:56.041
Do you do that a lot?

03:57.708 --> 03:59.750
Just the past couple of months.

03:59.833 --> 04:03.625
Stalking is sexy only applies
when it's men stalking women.

04:03.708 --> 04:08.250
When women are persistent
or stalking male characters,

04:08.333 --> 04:09.666
<i>they become the villain.</i>

04:09.750 --> 04:11.416
I just wanna be a part of your life.

04:11.500 --> 04:14.166
And this is the way you do it, huh?
Showing up at my apartment?

04:14.250 --> 04:15.750
What am I supposed to do?

04:15.833 --> 04:18.083
You won't answer my calls,
you change your number.

04:18.166 --> 04:20.333
I'm not gonna be ignored, Dan.

04:22.083 --> 04:25.541
[Lowe] <i>Every story needs a lead character</i>
<i>who commands attention,</i>

04:25.625 --> 04:28.458
someone as unique, special,
and one-of-a-kind

04:28.541 --> 04:30.208
as the lead in every other movie.

04:30.291 --> 04:33.416
Since all aspects of your protagonists
have to be remarkable,

04:33.500 --> 04:35.750
it's not enough for them
to just have a job.

04:35.833 --> 04:39.291
Whatever that job is,
they gotta job the shit out of it,

04:39.375 --> 04:43.625
especially if their job is the job:
the cop's job.

04:44.625 --> 04:46.375
-You think I'm crazy?
-Yeah.

04:46.458 --> 04:47.291
[Lowe] <i>In Hollywood,</i>

04:47.375 --> 04:50.458
<i>if you want crimes solved</i>
<i>and the bad guys brought to justice,</i>

04:50.541 --> 04:54.333
<i>top of the law-enforcement tree</i>
<i>is the maverick cop.</i>

04:54.416 --> 04:57.708
Now, that's a real badge, I'm a real cop,
and this is a real fucking gun.

04:57.791 --> 05:01.083
The maverick cop is a badass,
he doesn't listen to the chief.

05:01.166 --> 05:05.041
You wanna play some bullshit cowboy cop,
go do it in somebody else's precinct.

05:05.125 --> 05:07.333
They are completely dysfunctional.

05:07.416 --> 05:10.041
He's probably an alcoholic,
terrible father.

05:10.125 --> 05:13.916
You're my daughter, in my house,
and you'll respect me, got that?

05:14.000 --> 05:16.500
-Don't call me a fuck-up.
-Why shouldn't I?

05:16.583 --> 05:17.958
Mom calls you one.

05:18.041 --> 05:20.208
They only care about the job.

05:20.291 --> 05:22.250
No bullshit. You wanna kill yourself?

05:22.333 --> 05:24.625
You know why I don't do it? The job.

05:24.708 --> 05:26.541
Destroying everything in their path.

05:26.791 --> 05:28.250
-[gunshots]
-[alarms blaring]

05:32.041 --> 05:33.583
[Lowe] <i>Maverick cops keep coming,</i>

05:33.666 --> 05:37.458
<i>but the poster boy for loose cannons</i>
<i>of law enforcement remains:</i>

05:37.541 --> 05:40.083
<i>Clint Eastwood's</i> Dirty Harry.

05:40.166 --> 05:42.541
[Harry]
You've got to ask yourself one question:

05:42.625 --> 05:44.541
-"Do I feel lucky?"
-[alarm blaring]

05:44.625 --> 05:46.333
Well, do you, punk?

05:46.416 --> 05:49.666
[Nicholson] Dirty Harry <i>is a really toxic</i>
<i>example of this cliché.</i>

05:49.750 --> 05:51.583
That film tries so hard

05:51.666 --> 05:54.000
to put us on the side
of this beaten-down cop

05:54.083 --> 05:57.125
<i>who really just wants to let go</i>
<i>and shoot a bunch of people.</i>

05:57.208 --> 05:58.416
-[clicks]
-[man gasps]

05:58.500 --> 06:00.500
He exists by his own rules

06:00.583 --> 06:03.416
<i>and he does what he has to do</i>
<i>to get criminals.</i>

06:04.750 --> 06:08.541
It's painted that the legal system
is either incredibly stupid

06:08.625 --> 06:10.666
or run by bleeding heart liberals.

06:10.750 --> 06:13.791
What I'm saying is that man had rights.

06:15.291 --> 06:18.000
Well, I'm all broken up
about that man's rights.

06:18.083 --> 06:20.666
[Lowe] <i>Maverick law dictates</i>
<i>that there's only two things</i>

06:20.750 --> 06:24.041
<i>these cops care about,</i>
<i>and they're both shiny.</i>

06:24.125 --> 06:25.958
[chief] Your badge and gun, officer.

06:26.041 --> 06:28.833
[Ross] <i>It's a key moment in films</i>
<i>where the maverick cop</i>

06:28.916 --> 06:31.375
<i>hands in their gun and badge, like,</i>

06:31.458 --> 06:34.083
"You are no longer someone
who should be in this position."

06:34.166 --> 06:37.333
We know, the audience knows,
he's the only one who should have it.

06:37.416 --> 06:39.458
You're making me do this.
Give me your badge.

06:42.500 --> 06:43.458
Just take a couple...

06:44.791 --> 06:45.916
[Lowe] <i>In recent times,</i>

06:46.000 --> 06:48.833
<i>Hollywood has moved away</i>
<i>from making maverick cop movies,</i>

06:48.916 --> 06:51.833
<i>reflecting the disenchantment</i>
<i>with police officers</i>

06:51.916 --> 06:54.166
<i>who take the law into their own hands.</i>

06:54.250 --> 06:57.750
We are led to believe
that they're gonna do the right thing

06:57.833 --> 06:59.000
morally and ethically.

06:59.083 --> 07:02.125
The reality is,
that doesn't appear to be the case

07:02.208 --> 07:03.666
with a lot of police officers.

07:03.750 --> 07:08.500
It is something
that should be rethought by filmmakers,

07:08.583 --> 07:11.000
TV producers, and it is being rethought.

07:11.083 --> 07:14.541
[Lowe] <i>But the maverick cop</i>
<i>hasn't taken an early retirement.</i>

07:14.625 --> 07:16.833
<i>On TV, there's room for clichés</i>

07:16.916 --> 07:19.625
<i>to be worked into</i>
<i>three-dimensional characters.</i>

07:19.708 --> 07:21.583
<i>Kate Winslet's </i>Mare of Easttown

07:21.666 --> 07:24.000
<i>has a complex internal life,</i>
<i>but don't worry,</i>

07:24.083 --> 07:26.083
<i>she's still a cop who drinks hard,</i>

07:26.166 --> 07:28.458
<i>bends the rules, gets suspended...</i>

07:28.541 --> 07:29.625
Gun and badge.

07:29.708 --> 07:31.083
<i>...but still gets her man.</i>

07:31.166 --> 07:32.333
-[gunshots]
-[grunting]

07:34.916 --> 07:36.541
Hollywood loves a winner,

07:36.625 --> 07:39.208
but not every character
in your story can be a hero,

07:39.291 --> 07:42.625
unless it's set in the Marvel Universe,
which only 96% of movies are.

07:42.708 --> 07:45.041
Some characters are so destined to lose

07:45.125 --> 07:46.666
from the moment they walk on screen,

07:46.750 --> 07:50.541
that they might as well turn up
wearing a coffin and get it over with.

07:51.791 --> 07:54.166
<i>You're a secondary character in a film.</i>

07:54.250 --> 07:55.083
Thanks, John.

07:55.166 --> 07:56.625
[Lowe] <i>You've got a dangerous job.</i>

07:58.791 --> 08:00.708
<i>You're planning on calling it a day.</i>

08:00.791 --> 08:02.166
Tomorrow I'd like you to--

08:02.250 --> 08:05.208
-I'm resigning tomorrow, Frank.
-What?

08:05.291 --> 08:06.708
[Lowe] <i>Big mistake.</i>

08:06.791 --> 08:07.708
Al!

08:07.791 --> 08:09.125
[dramatic sting plays]

08:09.208 --> 08:10.291
[Schamus] <i>Dead man walking,</i>

08:10.375 --> 08:14.083
American cinema loves to cue

08:14.166 --> 08:18.500
people who are going to die by making
sure we know this is their last job.

08:18.583 --> 08:20.583
<i>They're about to retire, right?</i>

08:20.666 --> 08:23.208
I got three more days,
I wanna make the most of it.

08:23.291 --> 08:26.000
Maybe there's a retirement party
planned for you later.

08:26.083 --> 08:27.416
How about a speech?

08:27.500 --> 08:30.583
[King]
<i>And you've just got one more shift to do.</i>

08:31.166 --> 08:32.083
[gunshot]

08:32.708 --> 08:34.625
[Lowe] <i>And there are other classic ways</i>

08:34.708 --> 08:37.333
<i>to guarantee</i>
<i>death is just around the corner.</i>

08:37.416 --> 08:40.750
One way, you'll hear a character
talk about his family,

08:40.833 --> 08:42.500
about his aspirations...

08:42.583 --> 08:46.250
And I will marry a round American
woman and raise rabbits.

08:47.166 --> 08:50.125
If they start reflecting
on what they gonna do next... dead.

08:50.208 --> 08:53.958
Often in war films as well,
it will be the G.I. or whatever,

08:54.041 --> 08:56.250
<i>gets out a photo of his girlfriend...</i>

08:57.458 --> 09:01.500
and it's probably been in his pocket
for a while. Big mistake.

09:01.583 --> 09:04.208
-Please. Please.
-[dramatic music playing]

09:05.583 --> 09:08.250
-[bells tolling]
-[Lowe] <i>So once you're dead onscreen,</i>

09:08.333 --> 09:11.041
<i>your funeral will be attended</i>
<i>by loved ones</i>

09:11.125 --> 09:13.333
<i>and a solitary figure who,</i>
<i>for some reason,</i>

09:13.416 --> 09:15.791
<i>stands and stares from a long way away.</i>

09:15.875 --> 09:19.875
<i>It also allows the director</i>
<i>to get the wide shot of the ceremony.</i>

09:20.541 --> 09:23.500
<i>But </i>The Fast and the Furious
<i>takes it to another level.</i>

09:23.583 --> 09:26.583
<i>While Paul Walker</i>
<i>watches a funeral from a distance,</i>

09:26.666 --> 09:31.416
<i>Vin Diesel is watching Paul Walker</i>
<i>watch a funeral from a distance,</i>

09:31.500 --> 09:32.583
<i>from a distance.</i>

09:33.958 --> 09:36.083
<i>Of course, once the funeral is over,</i>

09:36.166 --> 09:38.041
<i>the grave site is the perfect setting</i>

09:38.125 --> 09:40.875
<i>to show a character's</i>
<i>fragile emotional state.</i>

09:40.958 --> 09:43.666
-[dramatic music playing]
-I love you.

09:43.750 --> 09:45.875
[Forrest]
Hey, Bubba. It's me, Forrest Gump.

09:45.958 --> 09:49.458
[Lowe] <i>And also a handy way</i>
<i>of explaining where we are in the plot.</i>

09:49.541 --> 09:53.166
I remember everything you said
and I got it all figured out.

09:53.250 --> 09:55.291
[Lowe] <i>Ed Harris does both.</i>

09:55.375 --> 09:57.833
<i>And just in case you're not sure</i>
<i>who he's talking to...</i>

09:57.916 --> 10:00.125
There's something I've gotta do, Barb.

10:00.208 --> 10:02.833
<i>...the filmmakers</i>
<i>carved it on the headstone for you.</i>

10:02.916 --> 10:04.083
<i>"His wife."</i>

10:05.375 --> 10:08.958
<i>But it's not always just talking</i>
<i>going on in the graveyard.</i>

10:09.041 --> 10:12.750
<i>Looks like there's one extra stiff</i>
<i>in the cemetery this morning.</i>

10:15.416 --> 10:17.541
One of the things I love most about cinema

10:17.625 --> 10:20.791
is the way it transports you
from your everyday life

10:20.875 --> 10:25.375
into an entirely fictional fantasy land
like Narnia, or France.

10:25.458 --> 10:28.833
-[French folk music playing]
-<i>The French have a word for clichés,</i>

10:28.916 --> 10:32.833
<i>but in cinema, one of the most</i>
<i>clichéd cities is Paris.</i>

10:32.916 --> 10:35.666
<i>But how can we tell we're in Paris?</i>

10:35.750 --> 10:37.375
<i>Because the director makes sure</i>

10:37.458 --> 10:40.750
<i>we can see the Eiffel Tower</i>
<i>through the bedroom window.</i>

10:42.625 --> 10:43.875
<i>The loft window.</i>

10:44.666 --> 10:46.166
<i>The train window.</i>

10:46.250 --> 10:48.125
<i>From the balcony.</i>

10:48.208 --> 10:49.958
<i>Through a clock.</i>

10:50.041 --> 10:50.958
<i>Unfortunately,</i>

10:51.041 --> 10:56.166
<i>that means the Eiffel Tower is on the top</i>
<i>of every invaders' to-destroy list.</i>

10:57.083 --> 10:58.916
Actors love working with props

10:59.000 --> 11:01.875
because like all good co-stars,
they never hog the scenes.

11:01.958 --> 11:03.750
And they're usually paid less.

11:03.833 --> 11:05.333
An everyday seeming prop

11:05.416 --> 11:08.541
can make even the most godlike figure
seem like a regular Joe.

11:08.625 --> 11:11.875
Admit it, this grocery-bag baguette combo
I'm holding

11:11.958 --> 11:14.708
has made me seem 26% more relatable.

11:14.791 --> 11:17.416
I haven't bought or eaten bread
in over ten years.

11:17.500 --> 11:18.916
The bag is only a cover

11:19.000 --> 11:22.250
to stop me from inadvertently absorbing
the carbs through my skin.

11:22.333 --> 11:24.083
All movie stars insist on it.

11:24.625 --> 11:27.750
<i>Often, lead actors</i>
<i>have to come across as regular Joes</i>

11:27.833 --> 11:29.375
<i>who do their own shopping,</i>

11:29.458 --> 11:33.541
<i>and a highly visible baguette sticking</i>
<i>out of the bag is parfait pour la job.</i>

11:34.125 --> 11:36.458
<i>It can also be ideal for hiding behind.</i>

11:37.083 --> 11:39.083
<i>The intensity of the performance</i>

11:39.166 --> 11:41.541
<i>is matched only</i>
<i>by the quantity of the bread.</i>

11:41.625 --> 11:44.375
Still warm.
It's the best bread I ever tasted.

11:45.041 --> 11:46.250
[Lowe] <i>What a professional.</i>

11:47.250 --> 11:51.833
One expressive prop
that actors love is the apple,

11:51.916 --> 11:54.833
despite it having
a shocking 19 grams of sugar.

11:57.375 --> 12:00.625
Tell me when you got enough
so I can spit this shit out.

12:04.958 --> 12:08.541
Eating in a scene
definitely is the cocky move.

12:08.625 --> 12:12.958
It's kind of like the ultimate
"I'm here and I don't care."

12:13.041 --> 12:15.041
[Lowe] <i>Defending the Starship </i>Enterprise.

12:16.750 --> 12:18.708
<i>Killing off an enemy army.</i>

12:19.625 --> 12:22.791
<i>Or snacking between meals</i>
<i>while meeting a superior officer.</i>

12:22.875 --> 12:24.375
Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

12:24.458 --> 12:26.708
[Lowe]
<i>An apple is the clichéd way of saying,</i>

12:26.791 --> 12:28.750
<i>"I'm too cool for school,"</i>

12:28.833 --> 12:31.208
<i>while lowering cholesterol</i>
<i>and promoting gut health.</i>

12:32.625 --> 12:34.166
The way your movie is cast

12:34.250 --> 12:36.458
depends on what kind of story
you're telling.

12:36.541 --> 12:39.208
Some stories require a director
to thoughtfully curate

12:39.291 --> 12:41.958
an ensemble
of subtly different personality types,

12:42.041 --> 12:45.125
<i>and some movies</i>
<i>just need a big guy who kills people.</i>

12:45.208 --> 12:46.875
[gunshots]

12:46.958 --> 12:49.416
Cinema likes
to tell us that the individual

12:49.500 --> 12:50.666
can take on the system,

12:50.750 --> 12:55.208
and one way it tells us this is possible
is via the one-man army.

12:55.291 --> 12:59.083
<i>You can see this right back</i>
<i>in the sort of Robin Hood,</i>

12:59.166 --> 13:01.166
<i>Errol Flynn films.</i>

13:01.958 --> 13:05.708
<i>You can see it going right through</i>
<i>the Western genre.</i>

13:06.500 --> 13:08.958
<i>You see it, arguably, in James Bond.</i>

13:11.666 --> 13:13.000
It changed in the '80s

13:13.083 --> 13:17.875
when your bodybuilders came into fashion.
Arnold Schwarzenegger, most famously,

13:17.958 --> 13:23.166
Stallone, they all of a sudden
didn't really look like blokes we knew.

13:23.250 --> 13:24.500
<i>They looked superhuman.</i>

13:26.208 --> 13:29.875
When you get Stallone
behind that weapon of mass destruction.

13:31.791 --> 13:34.416
<i>Twenty men being blown to smithereens.</i>

13:34.500 --> 13:39.083
Totally satisfying experience
in carnage and destruction,

13:39.166 --> 13:43.000
<i>with an absolute disregard</i>
<i>for human beings,</i>

13:43.083 --> 13:45.000
um, which you want in those movies.

13:45.083 --> 13:48.833
I think the invincibility
and the indomitability

13:48.916 --> 13:52.208
of the '80s action movie macho hero

13:52.291 --> 13:56.791
<i>became the key</i>
<i>for them becoming franchises.</i>

13:56.875 --> 13:58.583
<i>And then </i>Die Hard<i> came in,</i>

13:58.666 --> 14:02.541
<i>a film that starts out</i>
<i>relatively realistically.</i>

14:02.625 --> 14:05.166
<i>Bruce Willis seems like an ordinary bloke.</i>

14:05.250 --> 14:08.000
Drop it, dickhead. It's the police.

14:08.083 --> 14:09.333
Hang on, John!

14:09.416 --> 14:11.791
[Newman]
<i>But then, by the time of part five,</i>

14:11.875 --> 14:14.875
<i>basically, he could</i>
<i>take Superman down in part five.</i>

14:16.958 --> 14:20.125
The skills
are being physically very capable,

14:20.208 --> 14:22.458
<i>more than normal human beings.</i>

14:24.125 --> 14:27.041
They tend to be very much
the strong, silent type.

14:27.125 --> 14:30.166
The one place
where the one-man army will speak up

14:30.250 --> 14:33.666
