14:33.750 --> 14:34.916
We're married.

14:35.625 --> 14:38.791
[O'Hara] <i>The master of the form</i>
<i>is Arnold Schwarzenegger.</i>

14:38.875 --> 14:40.000
Consider that a divorce.

14:40.625 --> 14:43.666
Sure, your main character
can run around firing guns

14:43.750 --> 14:47.458
and bazookas at every school bus
like the hero they are,

14:47.541 --> 14:49.291
but if they wanna earn our respect,

14:49.375 --> 14:52.833
there comes a time when they'll
have to throw down those firearms

14:52.916 --> 14:54.541
and pick up their fists...

14:55.875 --> 14:56.958
with both hands.

14:59.416 --> 15:01.500
[Newman] <i>Throughout the silent era,</i>

15:01.583 --> 15:04.916
characters on screen had to
express themselves physically

15:05.000 --> 15:07.666
because people got bored
with the intertitle.

15:07.750 --> 15:09.833
<i>They laughed at the flowery prose.</i>

15:09.916 --> 15:12.833
So, what you get was lengthy fight scenes.

15:14.166 --> 15:17.208
<i>Officially,</i>
<i>the first staged fist-fight for film</i>

15:17.291 --> 15:20.875
<i>was the big fight</i>
<i>on top of and inside a train</i>

15:20.958 --> 15:22.875
<i>in </i>The Great Train Robbery.

15:22.958 --> 15:25.208
[Lowe] <i>Fast forward 100 years or so,</i>

15:25.291 --> 15:27.375
<i>and we still have guys</i>
<i>beating up on each other</i>

15:27.458 --> 15:30.750
<i>on moving trains,</i>
<i>just in slightly more expensive suits.</i>

15:31.916 --> 15:34.458
Something that I've loved
seeing in the last ten years

15:34.541 --> 15:39.291
is fight scenes getting more gritty
and gross to watch.

15:39.375 --> 15:40.833
[man grunts]

15:40.916 --> 15:44.000
The other kind of fantastic,
I think, cliché,

15:44.083 --> 15:46.916
that makes it more manageable
for us as an audience

15:47.000 --> 15:50.666
is when all of the attackers
come out one by one.

15:50.750 --> 15:52.333
[grunting]

15:52.416 --> 15:56.666
<i>In </i>Oldboy,
in the amazing scene in the corridor,

15:56.750 --> 16:00.791
you're placing your attention
on one kill at a time.

16:04.000 --> 16:06.916
It's kind of very related
to video games, I think,

16:07.000 --> 16:10.083
where this idea
that you might have all the skills

16:10.166 --> 16:14.375
and you're punching through,
but it just never ends.

16:15.333 --> 16:18.500
[Lowe] <i>The master of these "take a ticket</i>
<i>and wait till you're called" fights</i>

16:18.583 --> 16:20.458
<i>is the legendary Jackie Chan.</i>

16:21.208 --> 16:23.000
So Jackie Chan was my favorite.

16:24.041 --> 16:26.916
<i>The reason he was so popular</i>
<i>is he went against cliché</i>

16:27.000 --> 16:30.458
<i>and became the hero</i>
<i>who gets beat up the whole movie.</i>

16:31.291 --> 16:33.250
It's absurd what he's doing,

16:33.333 --> 16:36.208
<i>and it's without wires,</i>
<i>and it's death-defying.</i>

16:36.291 --> 16:38.250
<i>I feel like he's the person</i>

16:38.333 --> 16:41.208
that has had the most influence.
And it's all in camera.

16:42.083 --> 16:46.083
[Lowe] <i>And Jackie Chan's influence</i>
<i>can be seen in movies ever since.</i>

16:46.166 --> 16:51.333
Now you have fist fights that,
um, defy physiology,

16:51.416 --> 16:52.583
<i>physiognomy.</i>

16:52.666 --> 16:57.583
<i>If you hit somebody 50 times</i>
<i>and they get back up again,</i>

16:57.666 --> 16:59.375
<i>what is at stake?</i>

17:00.458 --> 17:02.000
What is finally gonna kill them?

17:03.333 --> 17:05.916
[Lowe]
<i>The evolution of big-screen punch-ups</i>

17:06.000 --> 17:09.041
<i>has seen the move more and more</i>
<i>from the balletic to the ballistic.</i>

17:09.708 --> 17:11.583
[Pugh] <i>It's that hand-to-hand combat</i>

17:11.666 --> 17:14.916
where they're smacking
each other's hands so fast,

17:15.000 --> 17:17.625
<i>that if you want to see what's going on,</i>
<i>you have to slow it down.</i>

17:18.250 --> 17:22.625
[Newman] <i>And then later on,</i>
<i>the recent rise of movies like </i>The Raid...

17:23.291 --> 17:25.791
<i>which are just nonstop fighting.</i>

17:26.416 --> 17:28.750
You can actually have a story
that is just people fighting.

17:32.416 --> 17:35.416
[Lowe] <i>From one type of intense</i>
<i>physical action to another...</i>

17:35.500 --> 17:36.708
Wait, Tarzan!

17:36.791 --> 17:38.416
[screams]

17:38.500 --> 17:40.375
[Lowe] <i>Sexy times and risqué nudity</i>

17:40.458 --> 17:42.666
<i>have been a Hollywood mainstay since,</i>

17:42.750 --> 17:44.291
<i>well, pretty much forever.</i>

17:44.375 --> 17:47.000
<i>In early cinema,</i>
<i>while studios pushed the boundaries</i>

17:47.083 --> 17:48.625
<i>of taste and decency,</i>

17:48.708 --> 17:50.958
<i>there was a growing pressure</i>
<i>to clean up their act</i>

17:51.041 --> 17:54.250
<i>and not present women</i>
<i>as being so free and promiscuous.</i>

17:54.333 --> 17:58.125
Take off your clothes,
get in here, and tell me all about it.

17:58.208 --> 18:02.833
In the early 1930s, you had things
like Barbara Stanwyck in <i>Baby Face,</i>

18:02.916 --> 18:07.166
who slept her way through the layers
of this giant New York bank.

18:07.250 --> 18:10.416
-Have you had any experience?
-Plenty.

18:10.500 --> 18:12.208
You had these Mae West characters

18:12.291 --> 18:16.416
<i>who were living it large,</i>
<i>drinking, smoking, whatever.</i>

18:16.500 --> 18:20.958
When I'm good, I'm very good,
but when I'm bad, I'm better.

18:22.375 --> 18:24.875
[Lowe] <i>After a series of scandals</i>
<i>in the early '20s,</i>

18:24.958 --> 18:27.625
<i>the press declared Hollywood</i>
<i>morally bankrupt,</i>

18:27.708 --> 18:30.041
<i>and a new code of conduct,</i>
<i>written by a priest,</i>

18:30.125 --> 18:33.041
<i>was championed by Republican</i>
<i>stick-in-the-mud Will Hays.</i>

18:33.125 --> 18:35.666
[man]
<i>Reputable producers signed up Will Hays</i>

18:35.750 --> 18:37.666
<i>to clean up the picture business...</i>

18:37.750 --> 18:43.291
That prohibited any sexual depravity
from being shown on screen.

18:43.375 --> 18:47.666
The vulgar, the cheap,
and the tawdry is out.

18:48.291 --> 18:51.625
[Lowe] <i>By the '30s,</i>
<i>the Hays Code imposed strict rules</i>

18:51.708 --> 18:55.583
<i>dictating what movies could</i>
<i>and couldn't show, mainly couldn't.</i>

18:55.666 --> 18:59.291
[Richard] <i>One of the actor's legs</i>
<i>had to be on the floor.</i>

19:00.416 --> 19:03.583
How are you supposed to fuck people
with one leg on the floor, I don't know.

19:03.666 --> 19:06.375
[Lowe] <i>But filmmakers</i>
<i>soon found ways to bend the rules,</i>

19:06.458 --> 19:10.583
<i>and the cinematic cliché</i>
<i>of sexual illusion became de rigueur.</i>

19:10.666 --> 19:15.708
How do you suggest the act of sex
without actually showing it?

19:17.708 --> 19:18.833
<i>Is it raining outside?</i>

19:18.916 --> 19:22.500
<i>There's a storm outside,</i>
<i>so there must be a storm in your heart</i>

19:22.583 --> 19:25.750
and possibly other regions too.

19:27.250 --> 19:30.583
[Jonathan] <i>You would go from them</i>
<i>in a sleeper cabin on a train</i>

19:30.666 --> 19:32.250
<i>to the train entering the tunnel.</i>

19:32.333 --> 19:35.333
The first few times that happens,
of course it's joyful,

19:35.416 --> 19:36.833
because those who know, know,

19:36.916 --> 19:39.041
and those who don't
aren't offended or troubled by it.

19:41.333 --> 19:42.708
[Helen] <i>In the 1960s,</i>

19:42.791 --> 19:46.708
<i>the big studios had lost their grip</i>
<i>on all of the cinema chains.</i>

19:46.791 --> 19:49.375
Independent cinemas had begun to sprout up

19:49.458 --> 19:52.791
and they were bringing in
exciting new films from Europe,

19:52.875 --> 19:57.958
<i>often which had exciting</i>
<i>and forbidden things like boobs.</i>

19:58.500 --> 20:01.291
[in Swedish]
I'll never forget you, darling Kerstin.

20:01.375 --> 20:05.416
As more European films
were visible to the American audience,

20:05.500 --> 20:06.333
Hollywood realized,

20:06.416 --> 20:08.958
"If we're gonna compete,
we have to get rid of the Hays Code."

20:09.958 --> 20:13.083
[Lowe] <i>The solution was an age-based</i>
<i>film rating system,</i>

20:13.166 --> 20:15.250
<i>which put sex back on screen,</i>

20:15.333 --> 20:19.333
<i>much to the dismay of people aroused</i>
<i>by shots of trains entering tunnels.</i>

20:19.416 --> 20:21.625
Sex in films
is never really very convincing,

20:21.708 --> 20:25.625
but at the same time,
it has its own stock set of clichés.

20:25.708 --> 20:28.041
[Pugh] <i>The music will be building,</i>

20:28.125 --> 20:32.041
<i>bodies will look amazing at all angles.</i>

20:32.125 --> 20:36.041
<i>Bras rarely ever fall off,</i>
<i>and you'll both finish at the same time.</i>

20:36.125 --> 20:38.083
It's so passionate.

20:39.458 --> 20:42.458
[Lowe] <i>Today, on-screen sex</i>
<i>may only be a right click away,</i>

20:42.541 --> 20:45.250
<i>but there's still one shot</i>
<i>Hollywood movies don't show,</i>

20:45.333 --> 20:46.458
<i>whatever the money.</i>

20:47.125 --> 20:50.958
It's that intensity, the build of music,
the build of passion.

20:51.041 --> 20:53.666
We all know what's gonna happen,
we don't need to see the next bit.

20:55.333 --> 20:59.208
[Lowe] <i>So movies are once again</i>
<i>forced to fall back on suggestion.</i>

20:59.291 --> 21:03.375
<i>A hand gripping the sheets,</i>
<i>a hand on a steamy window.</i>

21:03.458 --> 21:06.250
<i>Or even fire being blown out</i>
<i>of the end of a spaceship.</i>

21:06.333 --> 21:07.666
<i>A happy ending...</i>

21:08.708 --> 21:10.416
<i>is always guaranteed.</i>

21:12.750 --> 21:13.791
Who wrote this?

21:16.125 --> 21:19.375
<i>Need a character to express surprise?</i>
<i>Give them a drink.</i>

21:20.541 --> 21:21.666
What's a hard-on, Daddy?

21:23.291 --> 21:27.583
It's almost hard to find a comedy
that doesn't have some variation

21:27.666 --> 21:29.208
of the spit take in it.

21:29.291 --> 21:32.000
They used to call me anal girl.

21:32.083 --> 21:34.791
A spit take is something
that doesn't happen in real life,

21:34.875 --> 21:38.458
but you're gonna buy it
just because it's so fun to watch.

21:39.291 --> 21:43.000
[Lowe] <i>The spit take tells the audience</i>
<i>they've just seen something shocking...</i>

21:45.208 --> 21:46.625
Jeez, you smoke too?

21:46.708 --> 21:50.625
<i>...and is guaranteed to give any scene</i>
<i>an added spray of slapstick.</i>

21:50.708 --> 21:52.666
-What's this?
-Welcome. Oh!

21:52.750 --> 21:53.625
[groans]

21:55.208 --> 21:57.208
-Ma'am.
-Whale what?

21:58.291 --> 21:59.500
Welcome.

22:00.041 --> 22:00.958
[yells]

22:01.041 --> 22:03.125
Sorry, did I scare you?

22:03.208 --> 22:06.750
I didn't mean to.
I'm merely introducing our next cliché:

22:06.833 --> 22:08.125
The jump scare, which is--

22:08.208 --> 22:09.250
[yells]

22:12.541 --> 22:15.375
[Schamus] <i>Val Lewton was a filmmaker</i>
<i>who ran a low-budget unit</i>

22:15.458 --> 22:16.500
<i>at RKO Pictures,</i>

22:16.583 --> 22:19.833
<i>and he helped raise</i>
<i>a whole generation of filmmakers</i>

22:19.916 --> 22:22.958
who knew how to use mood
to really get to you.

22:23.583 --> 22:26.916
<i>In </i>Cat People,
<i>our heroine is being tracked,</i>

22:27.000 --> 22:28.708
<i>creating a sense of terror.</i>

22:31.833 --> 22:34.041
And of course the final hiss arrives.

22:35.458 --> 22:37.250
-[engine rumbling]
-[hissing]

22:37.333 --> 22:39.625
<i>Yet it's revealed</i>
<i>that it's actually a bus' brakes</i>

22:39.708 --> 22:42.416
as it pulls up,
and the sequence ends that way.

22:42.500 --> 22:46.958
[Lowe] <i>This was the first time</i>
<i>anyone had used a false scare in cinema,</i>

22:47.041 --> 22:50.500
<i>and the technique became known</i>
<i>as the "Lewton Bus."</i>

22:50.583 --> 22:52.958
<i>Now the jump scare comes in many forms:</i>

22:53.041 --> 22:55.583
<i>Things trying to get through</i>
<i>closed windows.</i>

22:56.708 --> 23:00.625
<i>People throwing themselves against fencing</i>
<i>when you're having a hug.</i>

23:01.750 --> 23:03.458
<i>And full-length coats.</i>

23:03.541 --> 23:04.625
[gasps]

23:04.708 --> 23:06.541
<i>Don't worry, it's not real leather.</i>

23:07.500 --> 23:09.416
<i>Given that the first false scare ever</i>

23:09.500 --> 23:12.083
<i>was from a bus</i>
<i>in a film called </i>Cat People,

23:12.166 --> 23:15.416
<i>it's ironic that the filmmakers'</i>
<i>most clichéd one today is...</i>

23:15.791 --> 23:16.916
-[screeches]
-[screams]

23:17.000 --> 23:18.333
<i>...the household cat.</i>

23:18.416 --> 23:20.333
-[cat screeches]
-[gasps, then groans]

23:20.416 --> 23:23.833
Cats are evil, and the cliché
about them being scary

23:23.916 --> 23:26.708
<i>is one of those clichés</i>
<i>that's completely based in fact.</i>

23:26.791 --> 23:30.125
[Nicholson] <i>Cats are just lurking</i>
<i>around the house hiding in closets.</i>

23:30.208 --> 23:31.208
[screams]

23:31.291 --> 23:33.083
So they can scare a person.

23:33.166 --> 23:36.208
[Lowe] <i>And their malevolence</i>
<i>isn't even limited to planet Earth.</i>

23:37.250 --> 23:38.333
[gasps]

23:38.416 --> 23:39.958
Cats are great for this,

23:40.041 --> 23:43.750
<i>because they are beings who exist</i>
<i>with us in our domestic spaces</i>

23:43.833 --> 23:46.958
but who couldn't give a shit
whether we live or die.

23:47.041 --> 23:48.375
[yelling]

23:51.625 --> 23:54.125
[Lowe] <i>If you happen to live</i>
<i>in a pet-free environment,</i>

23:54.208 --> 23:56.500
<i>there's always an option</i>
<i>to make people jump with a mirror.</i>

23:56.583 --> 23:57.708
[shower running]

23:57.791 --> 24:04.083
A mirror scare is one of
the greatest clichés in all of movies.

24:04.166 --> 24:05.291
[dramatic sting plays]

24:05.375 --> 24:06.791
<i>They always work,</i>

24:06.875 --> 24:11.708
because the idea that you're alone
and you shut the medicine cabinet,

24:11.791 --> 24:15.333
and then suddenly there's something
behind you is terrifying.

24:15.416 --> 24:17.083
[Ross] <i>In </i>American Werewolf in London...

24:17.166 --> 24:18.000
[screams]

24:18.083 --> 24:20.083
<i>...it's an amazing moment.</i>
<i>It's great fun, though,</i>

24:20.166 --> 24:24.416
that they can take something mundane
and give it that jolt, you know.

24:24.500 --> 24:25.458
You're not real.

24:25.541 --> 24:27.250
Every time we see a mirror,

24:27.333 --> 24:29.708
or see somebody in a bathroom,
we're worried.

24:29.791 --> 24:32.833
We are our most vulnerable
in the bathroom.

24:32.916 --> 24:36.666
It's a very private place.
I think that that's easy to exploit.

24:36.750 --> 24:37.666
[gasps]

24:37.750 --> 24:40.041
You can also do fake-outs with that.

24:40.125 --> 24:42.291
<i>You can put somebody into a bathroom</i>

24:42.375 --> 24:43.625
<i>and you can build tension.</i>

24:43.708 --> 24:46.041
<i>You don't have to have anything happen.</i>

24:46.666 --> 24:47.750
[man screams]

24:47.833 --> 24:49.791
[Lowe] <i>When you do hear someone</i>
<i>scream in a movie,</i>

24:49.875 --> 24:52.541
<i>chances are it could be our next cliché.</i>

24:52.625 --> 24:54.708
<i>But you probably didn't even realize it.</i>

24:56.125 --> 24:57.333
[screams]

24:57.416 --> 25:03.375
The Wilhelm scream is a scream
that was recorded originally in 1951.

25:03.458 --> 25:06.833
<i>The guy's walking through the Everglades,</i>
<i>then the alligator grabs his leg</i>

25:06.916 --> 25:09.416
<i>and he goes: </i>[mimics scream]

25:09.500 --> 25:10.375
[screams]

25:10.458 --> 25:12.375
Fast forward a couple of years later,

25:12.458 --> 25:15.125
and some sound editor
is looking for a scream

25:15.208 --> 25:19.041
<i>because poor Private Wilhelm</i>
<i>is struck by an arrow.</i>

25:19.125 --> 25:20.625
[sergeant] Wilhelm!

25:20.708 --> 25:22.458
Yeah, I'll just fill my pipe!

25:25.583 --> 25:26.500
[screams]

25:26.583 --> 25:29.625
Out comes-- Or let's say,
overlaid on top of him

25:29.708 --> 25:31.625
is the Wilhelm scream.

25:31.708 --> 25:34.083
[Lowe] <i>Wilhelm's scream</i>
<i>began to show up in Hollywood</i>

25:34.166 --> 25:37.916
<i>whenever a character was shot, pushed,</i>
<i>or obliterated by large plastic ants.</i>

25:38.000 --> 25:39.000
[man screams]

25:39.083 --> 25:41.958
<i>But when it was heard</i>
<i>in a galaxy far, far away,</i>

25:42.041 --> 25:43.875
<i>it became an insider joke.</i>

25:44.500 --> 25:45.500
[screams]

25:45.583 --> 25:47.541
It pops up in <i>Star Wars,</i>

25:47.625 --> 25:50.000
then George Lucas, Steven Spielberg,

25:50.083 --> 25:52.000
and everybody gets in on it.

25:52.833 --> 25:53.958
[screams]

25:54.041 --> 25:57.333
It's an industry joke.
Uh, Tarantino uses it...

25:57.416 --> 25:58.583
[screams]

25:58.666 --> 26:01.291
He's not using that by accident.

26:01.375 --> 26:05.375
That's him absolutely tapping
into the cliché of the sound.

26:05.458 --> 26:07.083
[man screams]

26:07.166 --> 26:09.166
There's something about the pitch of it,

26:09.250 --> 26:12.000
and it's strangely kind of reassuring

26:12.083 --> 26:16.125
that even in scenes of mayhem,
you will hear the Wilhelm scream.

26:16.208 --> 26:17.458
[screams]

26:17.541 --> 26:19.291
It's such a ridiculous in-joke now.

26:19.375 --> 26:21.708
We need a new scream, in my opinion.

26:21.791 --> 26:25.166
Hollywood likes to think of itself
as a paragon of equality,

26:25.250 --> 26:27.041
but apparently if you look closely,

26:27.125 --> 26:30.083
using a microscope,
which was invented by a man,

26:30.166 --> 26:34.000
there are occasional minor differences
in the way men and women are depicted.

26:35.250 --> 26:37.000
[roars]

26:37.083 --> 26:39.916
<i>The Smurfette principle</i>
<i>refers to the lone woman</i>

26:40.000 --> 26:42.416
<i>on a testosterone-infused adventure</i>

26:42.500 --> 26:45.500
<i>who ensures the filmmakers</i>
<i>tick that diversity box.</i>

26:45.583 --> 26:47.208
[Smurf] Hi, Smurfette!

26:47.291 --> 26:50.458
[Lowe] <i>The term originates</i>
<i>from the iconic Smurf world,</i>

26:50.541 --> 26:53.833
<i>where Smurfette is the only lady</i>
<i>in a land full of Smurf dudes.</i>

26:53.916 --> 26:55.166
[Smurfs whooping and whistling]

26:55.250 --> 26:58.958
This is a trope you'll see in everything,
from kids' cartoons...

26:59.041 --> 27:00.833
What are you doing? Get down.

27:00.916 --> 27:02.291
I'll teach that boy a lesson.

27:02.375 --> 27:04.291
...to <i>The Avengers...</i>

27:04.375 --> 27:06.166
I'm always picking up after you boys.

27:06.250 --> 27:08.583
<i>...to any kind of action film.</i>

27:08.666 --> 27:10.791
["Cherry Bomb" playing]

27:10.875 --> 27:14.541
It is the most cynical construct
in a movie

27:14.625 --> 27:18.708
<i>where they'll stick a woman in there</i>
<i>to have the guys ogle her.</i>

27:18.791 --> 27:19.708
What?

27:20.333 --> 27:24.250
Or they'll stick in a woman
to look at the guys askance

27:24.333 --> 27:26.250
<i>and tell them how immature they are.</i>

27:26.333 --> 27:29.291
I don't understand the physics
of how my toes hurt.

27:29.375 --> 27:30.666
[laughing]

27:30.750 --> 27:33.708
Children. I work with children.

27:36.958 --> 27:39.708
[Lowe] <i>Whether you're a token female,</i>
<i>or leading lady,</i>

27:39.791 --> 27:43.458
<i>chances are you'll find yourself</i>
<i>running to or from danger</i>

27:43.541 --> 27:44.625
<i>in high heels.</i>

27:44.708 --> 27:45.958
[roars]

27:46.958 --> 27:49.333
[Stock] <i>You've automatically</i>
<i>given a handicap to the women.</i>

27:49.416 --> 27:52.666
<i>They can't run in these heels,</i>
<i>but they don't discard them.</i>

27:52.750 --> 27:54.250
Even in recent films,

27:54.333 --> 27:57.458
they're still staggering around
in the middle of the road.

27:59.041 --> 28:01.458
The idea of women running in heels

28:01.541 --> 28:04.750
goes back to the issue
of Hollywood glamorizing women

28:04.833 --> 28:07.541
<i>to the point</i>
<i>which is completely impractical.</i>

28:08.875 --> 28:11.833
[Lowe] <i>With fast editing</i>
<i>and a leather outfit from a fetish store,</i>

28:11.916 --> 28:14.916
<i>your heroine can become</i>
<i>even more cartoonishly depicted.</i>

28:17.625 --> 28:20.833
Where I do take issue
is when a character decides

28:20.916 --> 28:24.583
what I need if I'm gonna fight
a bunch of people is high heels.

28:24.666 --> 28:29.125
Like Catwoman. You cannot fight
in those. You'll break an ankle.

28:29.208 --> 28:32.541
It takes a female character
who's a badass action hero,

28:32.625 --> 28:33.791
and it makes her phony.

28:33.875 --> 28:37.583
Another pet peeve. Sex scenes
with bras and fighting with heels.

28:37.666 --> 28:40.250
No, I'm not doing it. Not doing it.

28:42.583 --> 28:46.333
[Lowe] <i>Time for another of Tinseltown's</i>
<i>stock female character clichés:</i>

28:46.416 --> 28:48.166
<i>the manic pixie dream girl.</i>

28:48.583 --> 28:51.625
Blah, blah, blah, blah!

28:52.291 --> 28:55.541
I make a noise or I do something
no one has done before

28:55.625 --> 28:58.958
and then I can feel unique again,
even for a second.

28:59.041 --> 29:03.333
She is always extremely pretty,
she's always "quirky"...

29:03.416 --> 29:07.625
I gotta go bury this hamster
before the dogs eat him. Wanna help?

29:07.708 --> 29:09.500
-Having a weird pet.
-[yells] Rat!

29:09.583 --> 29:12.250
[Ellen] <i>That's a classic manic</i>
<i>pixie dream girl trait.</i>

29:12.333 --> 29:14.916
This is Rodolfo, he's a ferret.

29:15.000 --> 29:18.333
I am probably best known for coining
the phrase manic pixie dream girl,

29:18.416 --> 29:22.875
<i>and I coined that phrase in an article</i>
<i>that I wrote about a movie</i>

29:22.958 --> 29:24.500
<i>called</i> Elizabethtown.

29:24.583 --> 29:28.375
And in <i>Elizabethtown,</i>
there is an unusually pure example

29:28.458 --> 29:29.875
<i>played by Kirsten Dunst.</i>

29:29.958 --> 29:34.375
<i>And she is manic in the sense</i>
<i>that she talks and talk and talks.</i>

29:34.458 --> 29:37.416
I'm so happy we're here
having this conversation

29:37.500 --> 29:39.333
at 3:00 or whatever time it is.

29:39.416 --> 29:42.875
It's such a great time.
Everyone's sleeping but us.

29:42.958 --> 29:46.333
It's nice to have a conversation with you
and that you're really listening.

29:46.416 --> 29:49.541
Then dream girl,
this idea that it's a male fantasy

29:49.625 --> 29:52.625
that we can be depressed,
we can have nothing going,

29:52.708 --> 29:53.916
<i>and this woman will find us</i>

29:54.000 --> 29:57.416
<i>and she will set about</i>
<i>giving our life meaning.</i>

29:57.500 --> 29:59.458
I'm not used to girls like you.

30:00.541 --> 30:02.625
That's because I'm one of a kind.

30:02.708 --> 30:04.916
She shows him how to have fun

30:05.000 --> 30:09.083
and he offers her
absolutely nothing in return.

30:09.166 --> 30:14.625
It's a very, very potent fantasy for men
that there's one woman out there,

30:14.708 --> 30:17.708
one magical woman out there
that will save you.

30:19.875 --> 30:22.916
Often around two thirds of the way
into a movie, the writer realizes

30:23.000 --> 30:25.250
there's still a lot of story to tell
and not enough time.

30:25.333 --> 30:27.833
But it's okay. Just like in Beverly Hills,

30:27.916 --> 30:31.125
you can simply cut out any flab
you don't like using scissors.

30:31.208 --> 30:33.583
Enter montage mode.

30:33.666 --> 30:36.583
Well, when we first started talking
about montages,

30:36.666 --> 30:40.291
it would be about Eisenstein,
and the <i>Battleship Potemkin,</i>

30:40.375 --> 30:44.333
and just ways of cutting
together images from different angles...

30:44.416 --> 30:45.666
[dramatic music playing]

30:45.750 --> 30:48.458
<i>...that taught us that a movie</i>
<i>was not something</i>

30:48.541 --> 30:51.708
<i>you shoot straight ahead like you would</i>
<i>if you were sitting at a play.</i>

30:51.791 --> 30:54.333
<i>Battleship Potemkin</i>
really introduced audiences

30:54.416 --> 30:57.291
to editing for the first time,
and what you can do with editing.

31:00.000 --> 31:01.583
[Lowe] <i>This technique caught on,</i>

31:01.666 --> 31:04.333
<i>and quickly grasping</i>
<i>the new cinematic language,</i>

31:04.416 --> 31:07.125
<i>filmmakers began</i>
<i>montaging their brains out.</i>

31:07.208 --> 31:12.291
[narrator] <i>Apartment buildings, factories,</i>
<i>forests, ocean liners...</i>

31:12.375 --> 31:14.250
They're shorthand, really, montages.

31:14.333 --> 31:18.291
Getting across quite a lot of story
in a short space of time.

31:18.375 --> 31:19.375
Groovy.

31:20.583 --> 31:23.583
[Lowe] <i>With the arrival of one</i>
<i>famous sequence in the '70s,</i>

31:23.666 --> 31:26.666
<i>the montage began</i>
<i>punching above its weight.</i>

31:26.750 --> 31:31.375
The training sequences in <i>Rocky</i> are
the gold standard of training sequences.

31:32.750 --> 31:36.416
<i>I don't think anyone has ever</i>
<i>beaten a training sequence,</i>

31:36.500 --> 31:38.250
<i>a hard-at-work sequence, than</i> Rocky.

31:38.333 --> 31:42.708
[Lowe] <i>By </i>Rocky IV,<i> 31.9%</i>
<i>of its running time was montage.</i>

31:42.791 --> 31:44.416
<i>Almost a third of the film.</i>

31:44.500 --> 31:46.666
<i>The rest was mainly him hitting someone.</i>

31:50.458 --> 31:53.333
[Bogutskaya] <i>The fact that movies</i>
<i>can make us really feel</i>

31:53.416 --> 31:58.166
the work that goes into making something
seem very beautiful and very effortless,

31:58.250 --> 32:00.708
is, I think, an underappreciated cliché.

32:00.791 --> 32:04.625
-[man] <i>♪ We're gonna need a montage ♪</i>
-[chorus] <i>♪ Montage! ♪</i>

32:04.708 --> 32:08.750
The greatest of all montages is in,
of course, the South Park guys'

32:08.833 --> 32:10.125
<i>Team America: World Police.</i>

32:10.208 --> 32:12.625
<i>♪ You need a montage ♪</i>

32:12.708 --> 32:14.208
[Edelstein] <i>What's brilliant about that</i>

32:14.291 --> 32:18.416
is that not only is it sending up
the cliché of the montage,

32:18.500 --> 32:21.625
but at that point in the story,
we do need a montage.

32:21.708 --> 32:22.833
[sirens wailing]

32:22.916 --> 32:25.291
[Lowe]
<i>Little in the movies gets the pulse racing</i>

32:25.375 --> 32:28.458
<i>quite like a car</i>
<i>following another car really fast,</i>

32:28.541 --> 32:30.916
<i>but not quite fast enough to catch up.</i>

32:31.000 --> 32:35.083
<i>Ever since the white-hot adrenaline rush</i>
<i>of 1903's </i>Runaway Match,

32:35.166 --> 32:38.625
<i>action films have turned again</i>
<i>and again to the car chase.</i>

32:38.708 --> 32:41.833
In the hands of a skillful director
and skillful stunt drivers,

32:41.916 --> 32:44.583
and in the right script,
it can be the defining moment in the film.

32:44.666 --> 32:45.833
[engine revving]

32:46.500 --> 32:49.875
You know, <i>Bullitt,</i> of course, it is,
it's the defining moment of that film.

32:50.875 --> 32:53.750
[Lowe] <i>Over the years, finding new ways</i>
<i>to pump gas on the car chase</i>

32:53.833 --> 32:56.250
<i>has been a challenge for all movie makers.</i>

32:56.333 --> 33:00.708
<i>The French Connection</i> is a car
chasing an above-ground subway train,

33:00.791 --> 33:04.166
<i>and every squeal, every can that gets hit,</i>

33:04.250 --> 33:07.500
<i>every woman pushing a baby carriage...</i>

33:08.416 --> 33:11.916
it makes your stomach drop
at the potential for catastrophe.

33:12.750 --> 33:15.791
[Lowe] <i>But</i> <i>what's really under the hood</i>
<i>of a classic car chase?</i>

33:15.875 --> 33:18.416
The first thing I think of
when I think of car chases

33:18.500 --> 33:20.083
is, like, shot of the handbrake...

33:20.916 --> 33:22.750
<i>car skidding around the corner.</i>

33:22.833 --> 33:24.583
<i>That always has to be there.</i>

33:24.666 --> 33:28.458
There are carts and all types of debris
just flying everywhere.

33:31.500 --> 33:34.375
A place where a car shouldn't be,
put the car there.

33:36.208 --> 33:39.000
Going down stairs,
or you find something to...

33:45.125 --> 33:47.208
[John] <i>Car chases are really hard to write</i>

33:47.291 --> 33:49.250
<i>because you're describing</i>
<i>looking this way,</i>

33:49.333 --> 33:52.666
turning, things smashing,
and you're looking for, like,

33:52.750 --> 33:54.666
what's slightly new you can do about it.

33:55.708 --> 33:59.500
Go <i>has, I think, actually</i>
<i>a really good car-chase sequence in it.</i>

34:01.541 --> 34:04.125
<i>His car is stuck in an alley</i>
<i>in a really interesting way.</i>

34:05.250 --> 34:09.541
[Lowe] <i>Car chases have such wide appeal</i>
<i>that whole franchises are based on them.</i>

34:10.625 --> 34:14.083
The Fast and the Furious<i> started out</i>
<i>in the world of illegal racing,</i>

34:14.166 --> 34:16.791
<i>but its car chases</i>
<i>have been genetically modified</i>

34:16.875 --> 34:20.083
<i>into some of the most</i>
<i>ambitious sequences of all time.</i>

34:21.250 --> 34:24.208
The car chase is no longer
people on a road going very fast.

34:24.291 --> 34:26.708
It has to be dropping out of a plane.

34:26.791 --> 34:29.791
[dramatic music playing]

34:29.875 --> 34:32.708
Cars jumping out of giant buildings.

34:35.291 --> 34:39.958
Computer generated imagery nowadays
means that miracles are cheap.

34:41.208 --> 34:44.458
The physics have completely disappeared.

34:44.541 --> 34:47.916
<i>So now Vin Diesel can jump from one car</i>

34:48.000 --> 34:52.458
<i>and save his girlfriend mid-air</i>
<i>and survive.</i>

34:52.541 --> 34:55.833
You know that there
are no physical consequences

34:55.916 --> 34:59.333
to what you're seeing,
so nothing seems at stake anymore.

35:00.083 --> 35:03.583
[Lowe] <i>But other recent films</i>
<i>haven't gone for CGI techniques,</i>

35:03.666 --> 35:07.083
<i>producing nerve-jangling sequences</i>
<i>the old-fashioned way.</i>

35:07.875 --> 35:11.125
[Daniel] Baby Driver's <i>subverting</i>
<i>the cliché of car chases.</i>

35:11.208 --> 35:15.041
Often the music is
subservient to the imagery,

35:15.125 --> 35:17.833
the imagery is driving
what you're writing to,

35:17.916 --> 35:21.250
<i>in that they're both</i>
<i>literally, like, together.</i>

35:21.333 --> 35:23.875
[energetic rock music playing
over earbuds]

35:27.291 --> 35:30.458
With <i>Baby Driver,</i> it felt like a dance
the way that they move the car

35:30.541 --> 35:33.041
and the way they photographed it,
it was beautiful.

35:34.666 --> 35:37.916
<i>The synchronization between</i>
<i>the movement of the car chase</i>

35:38.000 --> 35:42.291
<i>and the songs, it felt more like a musical</i>
<i>than it felt like a car chase.</i>

35:48.250 --> 35:50.291
[Lowe] <i>Hollywood does not</i>
<i>have a great track record</i>

35:50.375 --> 35:52.916
when it comes to intelligent
portrayals of race.

35:53.000 --> 35:57.083
Something that I am perhaps
the first cisgendered white man

35:57.166 --> 36:00.041
brave enough to acknowledge in public.

36:00.916 --> 36:04.291
Call me a trailblazer,
heck, call me a savior if you must.

36:04.375 --> 36:07.125
It's not for me to say,
more for you to think.

36:08.291 --> 36:12.541
<i>Early representations of the white savior</i>
<i>may have been well meant...</i>

36:12.625 --> 36:14.291
Miss Jean Louise, stand up.

36:15.208 --> 36:17.041
[Lowe] <i>But from today's perspective...</i>

36:17.708 --> 36:19.083
Your father's passing.

36:19.166 --> 36:22.500
<i>...can be seen as the cinematic</i>
<i>Band-Aid for white guilt.</i>

36:23.250 --> 36:26.833
The white savior is a narrative
where a white person comes along

36:26.916 --> 36:30.333
and saves a Black person
from their struggle or suffering.

36:30.416 --> 36:33.750
What makes you think
colored people need your help?

36:34.666 --> 36:36.333
-Why do you care?
-Minny.

36:36.416 --> 36:38.500
Maybe you just wanna get
Aibileen in trouble.

36:38.583 --> 36:42.583
The Black characters are tools
for the white people to become better

36:42.666 --> 36:45.083
or, like, more fully show their humanity.

36:45.166 --> 36:49.875
If you go back to, you know,
<i>The Nun's Story</i> with Audrey Hepburn,

36:49.958 --> 36:53.166
<i>she is literally standing there</i>
<i>as this white nun</i>

36:53.250 --> 36:56.958
telling Black women
how to wash their children.

36:57.041 --> 36:59.625
Sister is teaching the mothers
how to wash their children.

36:59.708 --> 37:02.875
That was probably the most
egregious examples of this.

37:02.958 --> 37:05.833
[Lowe] <i>The white savior has appeared</i>
<i>in many guises since then,</i>

37:05.916 --> 37:08.416
<i>even as recently</i>
<i>as this Oscar winning tale</i>

37:08.500 --> 37:11.333
<i>of a white man</i>
<i>saving a world-class jazz pianist.</i>

37:11.875 --> 37:14.375
Gentleman says that
I'm not permitted to dine here.

37:14.458 --> 37:17.541
No, you don't understand.
He's playing tonight. He's the main event.

37:17.625 --> 37:20.833
I'm sorry, but it is the policy
of the restaurant.

37:20.916 --> 37:23.458
[Jones] Green Book <i>won Best Picture</i>
<i>in the same year</i>

37:23.541 --> 37:27.166
<i>to add insult to injury that</i> Black Panther
<i>was out and</i> BlacKkKlansman <i>were out.</i>

37:27.250 --> 37:29.875
So if you're interested
in stories about Black people,

37:29.958 --> 37:31.625
then there they are right there.

37:34.208 --> 37:38.625
[Lowe] <i>The yin to the white savior yang</i>
<i>can be seen in Disney's 1946 movie</i>

37:38.708 --> 37:41.750
Song of the South,
<i>depicting life on a plantation</i>

37:41.833 --> 37:43.958
<i>just after the abolition of slavery.</i>

37:44.041 --> 37:47.708
<i>Its central character, Uncle Remus,</i>
<i>has become synonymous</i>

37:47.791 --> 37:49.125
<i>with our next cliché,</i>

37:49.208 --> 37:50.708
<i>the magical negro.</i>

37:50.791 --> 37:55.083
The Uncle Remus character is there
to sort of help this young white boy,

37:55.166 --> 37:58.750
who lives on the plantation,
and he tells him these stories.

37:58.833 --> 38:02.125
--without a song jumping right out of it.

38:02.208 --> 38:05.750
<i>♪ Zip-a-dee-doo-dah, zip-a-dee-ay... ♪</i>

38:05.833 --> 38:08.333
[Jones]<i> This is another</i>
<i>old trope of the "happy sambo."</i>

38:08.416 --> 38:11.250
These terms are racist
and I'm using them in inverted commas.

38:11.333 --> 38:15.291
[man] <i>Hollywood turns out for the</i>
<i>20th annual presentation of awards.</i>

38:15.375 --> 38:17.916
The guy that played Uncle Remus
in the Disney version,

38:18.000 --> 38:21.666
<i>James Baskett, became</i>
<i>the first Black man to ever win an Oscar,</i>

38:21.750 --> 38:24.666
<i>although it was not a proper Oscar,</i>
<i>it was like an honorary Oscar</i>

38:24.750 --> 38:26.833
because they didn't feel that
he was competitive enough

38:26.916 --> 38:30.291
to be in the Best Actor
or the Best Supporting Actor categories.

38:30.375 --> 38:32.958
[Lowe] <i>The term was popularized</i>
<i>by the director Spike Lee,</i>

38:33.041 --> 38:37.458
<i>who identified that this offensive cliché</i>
<i>usually came with mystical powers.</i>

38:37.541 --> 38:40.000
You often don't know
where this character came from,

38:40.083 --> 38:45.000
why they're there, they just kind of exist
to offer guidance or wisdom.

38:45.083 --> 38:46.666
Don't worry about the vase.

38:46.750 --> 38:48.250
What vase?

38:50.791 --> 38:51.916
That vase.

38:52.000 --> 38:56.083
I find the magical negro trope
very unrealistic,

38:56.166 --> 38:58.333
because I personally don't feel
like helping white people

38:58.416 --> 39:00.208
with their problems on a day-to-day basis.

39:00.291 --> 39:02.625
[Lowe] <i>The John Coffey character</i>
<i>in </i>The Green Mile

39:02.708 --> 39:04.625
<i>is a simple uneducated man</i>

39:04.708 --> 39:07.666
<i>wrongly convicted</i>
<i>for the murder of two white children.</i>

39:07.750 --> 39:10.750
<i>On death row, he puts the time</i>
<i>that he has left on earth</i>

39:10.833 --> 39:13.875
<i>to the best possible use:</i>
<i>reassuring white folk.</i>

39:13.958 --> 39:15.166
Hello, boss.

39:15.250 --> 39:16.375
[Jones] <i>It's set in a prison,</i>

39:16.458 --> 39:18.416
<i>and then it's got</i>
<i>the white guard being forgiven</i>

39:18.500 --> 39:21.208
for executing a Black man
for a crime he didn't commit

39:21.291 --> 39:22.333
by the Black man,

39:22.416 --> 39:25.666
which is just such
obvious kind of reassuring,

39:25.750 --> 39:29.958
soothing fantasy for white guilt
that I find it impossible to watch.

39:30.041 --> 39:35.291
[Lowe] <i>The magical negro cliché was even</i>
<i>taken to its ultimately divine conclusion</i>

39:35.375 --> 39:37.166
<i>with Morgan Freeman in</i> Bruce Almighty.

39:38.166 --> 39:39.250
I'm God.

39:39.333 --> 39:42.958
Morgan Freeman plays a magical negro
exceptionally well.

39:43.041 --> 39:47.125
He was a magical God negro,
like he is the God of magical Negros.

39:47.208 --> 39:50.833
Man, Morgan Freeman has
redefined the magical negro, I think.

39:51.416 --> 39:53.333
[Lowe] <i>And in </i>The Legend of Bagger Vance,

39:53.416 --> 39:56.833
<i>the magical negro perhaps</i>
<i>achieves his highest purpose:</i>

39:56.916 --> 39:58.958
<i>improving a white guy's handicap.</i>

39:59.041 --> 40:00.958
I could've killed you out there.

40:01.625 --> 40:04.625
Oh, no, sir, see, I set myself
directly in front of you.

40:04.708 --> 40:08.083
Judging by how you was hitting them balls,
that's where I'd be out of harm's way.

40:08.166 --> 40:11.208
[Aisha] <i>One of the things</i>
<i>that's just so offensive about it,</i>

40:11.291 --> 40:12.916
that movie's set in the '30s

40:13.000 --> 40:15.208
when lots of Black people
were getting lynched,

40:15.291 --> 40:17.666
uh, the KKK was everywhere,

40:17.750 --> 40:20.291
and yet this character
played by Will Smith

40:20.375 --> 40:22.375
<i>is just concerned with Matt Damon</i>

40:22.458 --> 40:25.166
<i>getting his swing perfected</i>
<i>on the golf course.</i>

40:25.250 --> 40:30.916
It's just you, that ball, that flag...

40:31.000 --> 40:34.000
Actors gotta get a check
just like everybody else.

40:34.083 --> 40:35.833
I've done jobs I don't wanna do.

40:35.916 --> 40:40.375
<i>I don't think Will Smith is at home</i>
<i>re-watching </i>The Legend of Bagger Vance.

40:40.458 --> 40:43.291
Some white person somewhere
in, like, Ohio is re-watching it,

40:43.375 --> 40:46.000
so I hope they're enjoying it.

40:49.458 --> 40:51.583
[Lowe] <i>Why bother dreaming up</i>
<i>a convoluted plot line</i>

40:51.666 --> 40:55.458
<i>when a cliché guaranteed to drive</i>
<i>any revenge narrative can simply be...</i>

40:55.541 --> 40:57.250
You killed my father.

40:57.333 --> 40:59.208
[Lowe] <i>Whether it's a classic Western...</i>

40:59.291 --> 41:00.500
You killed my father!

41:00.583 --> 41:03.166
<i>...or even an arachnid-based blockbuster.</i>

41:03.250 --> 41:05.041
You killed my father.

41:05.125 --> 41:06.708
[Lowe] <i>John Wick, on the other hand,</i>

41:06.791 --> 41:09.958
<i>doesn't quite need as much incentive</i>
<i>for his killing sprees.</i>

41:10.250 --> 41:12.208
[in Russian]

41:18.416 --> 41:20.958
Animals in movies
often seem to sense things

41:21.041 --> 41:24.041
their human stars
they're sharing the screen with don't.

41:24.125 --> 41:26.708
Could it be they're somehow
more intelligent than we are?

41:26.791 --> 41:29.166
No, half those idiots
still shit while they walk.

41:29.250 --> 41:33.875
But they do have
an almost supernatural nose for danger.

41:34.916 --> 41:36.416
<i>God's creatures:</i>

41:36.500 --> 41:38.625
<i>The Geiger counter of the supernatural.</i>

41:38.708 --> 41:40.083
There's something wrong.

41:40.166 --> 41:44.125
[Lowe] <i>If something spooky's going on,</i>
<i>they'll be the first to let you know.</i>

41:44.208 --> 41:46.625
<i>Horses, tap once for the dead,</i>

41:46.708 --> 41:48.125
<i>three times for the undead.</i>

41:48.208 --> 41:50.416
[neighing]

41:51.166 --> 41:52.625
See? He knows.

41:52.708 --> 41:55.416
[Lowe] <i>Worried about your son</i>
<i>being the prince of darkness?</i>

41:55.500 --> 41:58.416
<i>Simply cast a pack</i>
<i>of Beelzebub-sniffing baboons.</i>

41:58.583 --> 42:00.291
-[howling]
-[screaming]

42:01.666 --> 42:05.666
<i>But in Hollywood,</i>
<i>evil's worst enemy is man's best friend.</i>

42:05.750 --> 42:07.875
The role of the dog is to warn you.

42:07.958 --> 42:11.083
The role of the dog is to say
there's something not quite right here.

42:11.166 --> 42:13.416
-[whining, barking]
-What's the matter, E Buzz?

42:13.500 --> 42:15.041
[Lowe] <i>From unseen ghosts...</i>

42:15.125 --> 42:16.291
What are you doing?

42:16.375 --> 42:18.166
<i>...to wannabe vampires.</i>

42:20.416 --> 42:22.666
<i>And it's not just the supernatural.</i>

42:22.750 --> 42:25.958
<i>A sensitive pooch</i>
<i>can also sniff out earthly evil.</i>

42:26.625 --> 42:27.708
[barking]

42:27.791 --> 42:30.125
<i>Ted Bundy, you've been busted.</i>

42:30.208 --> 42:31.625
[growling]

42:32.416 --> 42:34.875
<i>Of all the things</i>
<i>it's dangerous to be in movies--</i>

42:34.958 --> 42:38.875
<i>Henchmen, stormtrooper,</i>
<i>a cop two days from retirement.</i>

42:38.958 --> 42:41.875
<i>--right up near the top of the list</i>
<i>must be gay or lesbian.</i>

42:41.958 --> 42:45.208
You know, Hollywood gets a rap
for making its gay characters expendable.

42:45.291 --> 42:46.375
Listen to me!

42:46.458 --> 42:48.458
[Lowe]
<i>One of Hollywood's earliest exploitations</i>

42:48.541 --> 42:50.125
<i>of gay and lesbian relationships...</i>

42:50.208 --> 42:52.500
I have loved you the way they said.

42:52.583 --> 42:55.708
<i>...was </i>The Children's Hour,
<i>an unsympathetic account</i>

42:55.791 --> 42:58.291
<i>of two teachers,</i>
<i>Audrey Hepburn and Shirley MacLaine,</i>

42:58.375 --> 43:00.250
<i>who are accused of a lesbian affair,</i>

43:00.333 --> 43:02.625
<i>which leads to one of them</i>
<i>committing suicide.</i>

43:05.250 --> 43:09.375
<i>But while Hollywood may try to highlight</i>
<i>the issues of LGBTQ characters,</i>

43:09.458 --> 43:12.166
<i>it does kind of seem</i>
<i>to kill them in the process.</i>

43:13.875 --> 43:18.166
At times when it's touching
on the actual misery

43:18.250 --> 43:23.875
or torture of gay people,
I think it's actually okay as a cliché.

43:25.416 --> 43:28.083
<i>So for instance, in</i> Brokeback Mountain,

43:28.166 --> 43:31.041
<i>it's not a love story,</i>
<i>it's about persecution</i>

43:31.125 --> 43:32.583
over many, many years.

43:32.666 --> 43:34.708
And so when that death finally occurs,

43:34.791 --> 43:37.625
it's actually logically
dictated by the film.

43:37.708 --> 43:39.333
[Lureen] <i>He was only 39 years old.</i>

43:39.416 --> 43:43.750
Well, award season does really love
a biopic about a dead gay person.

43:43.833 --> 43:46.625
<i>They love a film</i>
<i>where someone dies tragically.</i>

43:47.625 --> 43:51.250
Yeah, I can attest to that
because I played a gay character

43:51.333 --> 43:52.708
in <i>Can You Ever Forgive Me?</i>

43:52.791 --> 43:56.416
And the character I played,
Jack Hock, did die of AIDS.

43:56.500 --> 43:59.625
You did fuck your way
through Manhattan. I mean...

44:01.958 --> 44:03.458
I'd like that on my tombstone.

44:03.541 --> 44:05.500
So yes, that is obviously true.

44:07.625 --> 44:12.708
[Lowe] <i>In fact, around 40% of LGBTQ</i>
<i>characters nominated for an Oscar</i>

44:12.791 --> 44:14.833
<i>don't make it to the end credits.</i>

44:18.250 --> 44:23.458
A great way to put a character in peril
is to rely on the tech and the tech fails.

44:23.541 --> 44:26.833
<i>In </i>Mission Impossible,
<i>when he's climbing that building,</i>

44:26.916 --> 44:28.166
you're like, "Cool."

44:28.250 --> 44:29.416
But then you think,

44:29.500 --> 44:32.416
now you're on the outside,
and that tech fails...

44:33.458 --> 44:35.458
<i>And so now you immediately have drama.</i>

44:35.541 --> 44:39.583
[Lowe] <i>Who hasn't scaled a building</i>
<i>and forgotten to bring a glove charger?</i>

44:39.666 --> 44:42.666
<i>Though most big tech fails</i>
<i>are more down-to-earth.</i>

44:42.750 --> 44:44.416
[engine grinding]

44:44.500 --> 44:48.916
We've all gotten into a car
and turned that thing and it didn't start.

44:49.000 --> 44:51.000
[grinding continues]

44:52.875 --> 44:55.083
A few years ago,
everybody got a cell phone.

44:55.166 --> 44:58.375
This is my last communication--
Oh, the battery died.

44:58.458 --> 45:00.291
[cell phone battery beeping]

45:00.375 --> 45:04.291
The tech has to fail for the story
to be engaging and for us to be like,

45:04.375 --> 45:05.541
"What will they do next?"

45:08.666 --> 45:10.958
[Lowe]<i> Whether it be</i>
<i>cutting-edge climbing technology,</i>

45:11.041 --> 45:15.333
<i>a car, or a cell phone,</i>
<i>the tech fail always signals danger.</i>

45:16.083 --> 45:16.916
[screams]

45:20.333 --> 45:23.875
<i>Angry and seated at a desk?</i>
<i>Then do the angry desk sweep.</i>

45:23.958 --> 45:25.625
Shit!

45:26.208 --> 45:29.875
[Lowe] <i>Has a maverick cop foiled</i>
<i>your master plan for making billions?</i>

45:31.833 --> 45:35.458
<i>Are you a world renowned neurosurgeon</i>
<i>with busted hands?</i>

45:37.416 --> 45:40.708
<i>Or a high-flying military lawyer</i>
<i>up against a five-star general?</i>

45:40.791 --> 45:43.916
Thank you for playing
"Should we or should we not

45:44.000 --> 45:47.000
follow the advice
of the galactically stupid!"

45:47.083 --> 45:50.083
[Lowe] <i>But what the hell,</i>
<i>kick a chair while you're at it.</i>

45:51.333 --> 45:55.000
<i>Maverick cop Jake Gyllenhaal</i>
<i>has a real challenge with this desk.</i>

45:55.083 --> 45:57.458
<i>His stuff just doesn't go anywhere.</i>

45:59.000 --> 46:01.250
<i>No wonder the keyboard gets a beating.</i>

46:04.041 --> 46:07.458
Every hero needs a villain
to go up against.

46:07.541 --> 46:10.000
It's taken us a while
to get around to him,

46:10.083 --> 46:12.583
but he's been expecting you, Mr. Bond.

46:14.833 --> 46:16.541
<i>If your hero is good-looking,</i>

46:16.625 --> 46:20.083
<i>this means the clichéd bad guy</i>
<i>has to be the polar opposite,</i>

46:20.166 --> 46:23.666
<i>and the filmmakers usually</i>
<i>make it easy for us to spot who they are.</i>

46:23.750 --> 46:26.625
Allow me to introduce myself.

46:27.958 --> 46:31.166
I am Ernst Stavro Blofeld.

46:31.250 --> 46:35.125
We make them other than us.
We make them ugly, disfigured.

46:35.208 --> 46:38.833
Some scar to say that they're evil,
even if they're a lion.

46:38.916 --> 46:40.208
Murderer.

46:40.291 --> 46:43.333
You're telling a story,
you're telling the audience

46:43.416 --> 46:46.583
that your character has been
involved in nefarious activity

46:46.666 --> 46:49.541
<i>and probably physical violence</i>
<i>in the past.</i>

46:49.625 --> 46:53.625
--and fulfill your destiny.

46:53.708 --> 46:56.416
The disfigured villain goes way back.

46:56.500 --> 47:00.250
<i>Back to silent film.</i>
<i>You have, obviously, Lon Chaney</i>

47:00.333 --> 47:01.791
<i>in </i>Phantom of the Opera,

47:01.875 --> 47:05.083
with the hairpins
stretching his nostrils out.

47:06.458 --> 47:11.708
The problem with that sort of
characterization is the fact that then,

47:11.791 --> 47:14.125
in real life, it translates to people

47:14.208 --> 47:16.625
who have those physical disfigurements

47:16.708 --> 47:20.625
being seen by other people
as dangerous, as scary,

47:20.708 --> 47:22.125
as someone to shun.

47:22.208 --> 47:28.125
Certainly that equating of disfigurement
in some way turning you into a psychopath

47:28.208 --> 47:30.833
is incredibly insulting.

47:30.916 --> 47:33.541
A lot of villains
are more cultured than the hero.

47:33.625 --> 47:37.083
You know, you'll have villains
who talk about their love of Beethoven.

47:37.750 --> 47:38.916
You don't like Beethoven.

47:39.000 --> 47:40.833
[Mark] <i>Loving the finer things in life...</i>

47:40.916 --> 47:42.541
You don't know what you're missing.

47:42.625 --> 47:44.583
...gives a sense
that there is another side,

47:44.666 --> 47:49.041
another side to them, which enhances
the fact that they're, you know, evil.

47:49.125 --> 47:54.583
I ate his liver with some fava beans
and a nice Chianti.

47:57.208 --> 47:58.708
They're often British.

47:58.791 --> 48:01.708
That tends to be
a real subcategory of villains.

48:01.791 --> 48:04.916
In Hollywood, they thought
that an English accent

48:05.000 --> 48:07.083
was a shorthand for sophistication.

48:07.750 --> 48:11.291
Do you intend to cooperate with us?
I'd like a simple yes or no.

48:11.375 --> 48:16.333
If your baddie had an English accent,
then the hero was dealing with something

48:16.416 --> 48:18.041
that wasn't just plain brutish.

48:18.125 --> 48:20.208
There was something else behind it.

48:20.291 --> 48:23.291
Somehow casting an English actor,
because we're cheap,

48:23.375 --> 48:25.083
and you can say the dialogue,

48:25.166 --> 48:28.708
and you can say gibberish dialogue
with great conviction.

48:28.791 --> 48:33.625
History, tradition, culture,
are not concepts.

48:33.708 --> 48:37.000
These are trophies
I keep in my den as paperweights!

48:37.083 --> 48:41.916
The monologue is a cliché
because it's the stuff of drama.

48:42.000 --> 48:46.916
Everything that has transpired
has done so according to my design.

48:47.000 --> 48:50.791
It's the writer allowing the audience to
understand where this character comes from

48:50.875 --> 48:52.708
and why they're doing what they're doing.

48:52.791 --> 48:57.625
I had a villain's monologue
in the final sequence of <i>Logan.</i>

48:57.708 --> 49:01.083
I'm giving this verse
about why I've done what I've done

49:01.166 --> 49:02.708
and killed his family, all this.

49:02.791 --> 49:06.125
I realized we needn't stop perfecting
what we eat and drink.

49:06.208 --> 49:08.291
We use those products
to perfect ourselves.

49:08.375 --> 49:10.500
And halfway through my monologue...

49:11.875 --> 49:14.000
he kills me, deservedly.

49:14.833 --> 49:18.666
There comes a time when every movie
simply has to stop happening.

49:18.750 --> 49:21.125
And that time is known as the end.

49:21.208 --> 49:23.458
It's when all the narrative plates
you've been spinning

49:23.541 --> 49:26.916
have to suddenly weave together
in a better metaphor than this.

49:27.000 --> 49:29.833
It's time for
the movie's climactic endgame,

49:29.916 --> 49:33.333
<i>and there are only</i>
<i>so many forms that can take.</i>

49:35.375 --> 49:37.750
<i>The shower scene in Hitchcock's </i>Psycho

49:37.833 --> 49:41.916
<i>with Janet Leigh is seen</i> by many
<i>to be the inspiration</i> <i>for our next cliché.</i>

49:42.000 --> 49:43.958
<i>And for locks on bathroom doors.</i>

49:44.041 --> 49:48.833
Hitchcock popularized this notion
that it would be women going through

49:48.916 --> 49:53.125
these horrific circumstances,
and he set up this expectation

49:53.208 --> 49:56.500
<i>that women would play</i>
<i>a central role in thrillers.</i>

49:57.583 --> 50:00.250
[Lowe] <i>Eighteen years later,</i>
<i>Janet Leigh's daughter,</i>

50:00.333 --> 50:02.208
<i>Jamie Lee Curtis, played a role</i>

50:02.291 --> 50:06.500
<i>which made her an icon of the cliché</i>
<i>now known as the final girl.</i>

50:09.083 --> 50:13.250
The monster versus the final girl,
Jamie Lee Curtis in <i>Halloween,</i>

50:13.333 --> 50:15.708
symbolically stands as the first.

50:15.791 --> 50:17.916
She is the blueprint, the prototype.

50:18.000 --> 50:21.041
The final girl is the one girl
who doesn't have sex,

50:21.125 --> 50:23.333
who's more innocent than her friends.

50:23.416 --> 50:26.791
You must have a small fortune stashed
from babysitting so much.

50:26.875 --> 50:28.375
Guys think I'm too smart.

50:28.458 --> 50:29.916
Because she's not having sex,

50:30.000 --> 50:33.333
she's somehow miraculously
more observant than all of her friends

50:33.416 --> 50:35.125
and senses something wrong first.

50:35.208 --> 50:37.708
If you want
a really good final-girl movie,

50:37.791 --> 50:40.416
you need to take a group of friends...

50:40.500 --> 50:44.125
If you listen to the old timers in town,
they'll tell you he's still out there.

50:44.208 --> 50:48.083
They've all gone off
on a weekend party somewhere.

50:48.166 --> 50:51.041
You need to give them
a spurious reason to go off

50:51.125 --> 50:54.458
in different directions,
and get up to any kind of mischief.

50:54.541 --> 50:56.250
[suspenseful music playing]

50:56.333 --> 51:00.291
That's another cliché, another rule:
If you do the dirty deed,

51:00.375 --> 51:01.541
you're gonna die.

51:03.250 --> 51:05.916
One by one they are dispatched.

51:06.000 --> 51:08.125
[cackling]

51:09.583 --> 51:11.791
There's always a lull in these movies

51:11.875 --> 51:14.583
where everyone thinks
the killer might be dead.

51:16.416 --> 51:19.625
Then it all comes crashing down
and she has to prove herself again.

51:21.666 --> 51:25.458
But she survives and she becomes
the audience surrogate.

51:28.166 --> 51:29.875
[woman screaming]

51:31.583 --> 51:34.000
I think slasher films
and all their clichés

51:34.083 --> 51:39.625
would be completely dead right now
if there hadn't existed <i>Scream.</i>

51:39.708 --> 51:43.250
[Lowe] Scream <i>turned the cliché</i>
<i>on its blood-splattered head</i>

51:43.333 --> 51:47.541
<i>by dispatching assumed final girl</i>
<i>Drew Barrymore in its opening moments.</i>

51:49.291 --> 51:55.416
I think the <i>Scream</i> franchise
really addressed the horror fans

51:55.500 --> 52:00.875
and their knowledge of the clichés,
and sort of turned it on its head.

52:00.958 --> 52:02.500
What's the point? They're all the same.

52:02.583 --> 52:04.916
Some stupid killer
stalking some big-breasted girl

52:05.000 --> 52:07.833
who's running up the stairs when
she should be going out the door.

52:07.916 --> 52:08.750
It's insulting.

52:08.833 --> 52:11.666
[Lowe] <i>But the final girl</i>
<i>has appropriately survived.</i>

52:13.041 --> 52:14.875
<i>Today, she's better prepared.</i>

52:15.791 --> 52:17.083
Fuck your family.

52:17.166 --> 52:19.250
[Pugh] <i>We're now giving her power</i>
<i>towards the end,</i>

52:19.333 --> 52:21.750
and we're making people
scared of her towards the end.

52:21.833 --> 52:23.250
Eat it, bitch!

52:24.041 --> 52:27.166
She is sometimes more deadly
than the people

52:27.250 --> 52:29.958
that she's actually
kind of fighting to survive.

52:31.958 --> 52:34.625
And technically,
has a much bigger body count

52:34.708 --> 52:38.000
than any of the would-be "killers"
in the movie.

52:39.583 --> 52:43.333
I think it's kind of evolved
as a cliché now

52:43.416 --> 52:46.125
into almost
a kind of a comfort-food finale.

52:47.291 --> 52:48.125
Fuck.

52:49.375 --> 52:53.041
[Lowe] <i>Next up: that explosive</i>
<i>movie cliché, the ticking time bomb.</i>

52:53.666 --> 52:55.750
[Hargrave] <i>There's a bomb,</i>
<i>and there's a ticking clock.</i>

52:55.833 --> 52:58.208
If the hero doesn't act,
large amounts of people die.

52:58.291 --> 53:00.000
So inherently dramatic.

53:00.083 --> 53:02.958
-How much time left?
-Twenty seconds!

53:03.041 --> 53:06.833
[Edelstein] <i>Doesn't matter what movie,</i>
<i>when you watch the numbers click down,</i>

53:06.916 --> 53:08.583
your heart is in your mouth.

53:10.416 --> 53:14.083
[Lowe] <i>In its classic form,</i>
<i>this cliché always comes down to the wire.</i>

53:14.166 --> 53:15.166
You think?

53:15.250 --> 53:18.541
Cut the red or the blue,
the red or the blue?

53:18.625 --> 53:20.625
[suspenseful music playing]

53:24.250 --> 53:27.583
It's one of the great
non-action climaxes ever.

53:27.666 --> 53:28.833
They look sexier now.

53:28.916 --> 53:32.500
<i>Often it's someone trying to hack in</i>
<i>and stop the countdown.</i>

53:33.458 --> 53:35.541
[automated voice]
<i>Cerberus has been deactivated.</i>

53:35.625 --> 53:39.375
If it's your hero defusing the time bomb,
you know he or she is gonna do it.

53:39.458 --> 53:41.041
The fun thing for us is going,

53:41.125 --> 53:44.875
"How close to one
are they gonna take it, really?"

53:44.958 --> 53:48.500
<i>And it goes to one so many times.</i>

53:54.166 --> 53:57.750
[Lowe]<i> The must-have at the end</i>
<i>of a romance is the lover's mad dash</i>

53:57.833 --> 54:01.833
<i>where one of the pair has a frenzied race</i>
<i>against time and geography</i>

54:01.916 --> 54:04.541
<i>to declare undying love to their partner.</i>

54:04.625 --> 54:08.875
Often, that will involve
a last-minute lover's dash to the airport,

54:08.958 --> 54:10.833
<i>or to stop a wedding happening.</i>

54:10.916 --> 54:13.125
The Graduate's<i> a classic one of that.</i>

54:17.208 --> 54:19.541
Oh, Jesus, God, no.

54:20.208 --> 54:23.500
[Lowe] <i>Having chased and convinced</i>
<i>their other half of their eternal love,</i>

54:23.583 --> 54:27.666
<i>their reward is a passionate kiss,</i>
<i>usually in bad weather conditions.</i>

54:28.333 --> 54:32.541
[King] <i>It's when you're so wrapped up</i>
<i>in kissing the person you love</i>

54:32.625 --> 54:35.708
that you're not even aware
of the terrible weather.

54:35.791 --> 54:38.666
And I think that's what happened
in <i>Four Weddings and a Funeral,</i>

54:38.750 --> 54:41.708
was these two people
having all these obstacles

54:41.791 --> 54:46.708
not to be together,
and finally, in the rain...

54:49.000 --> 54:51.250
Is it still raining? I hadn't noticed.

54:55.375 --> 54:58.458
Greta Gerwig, the director,
did that for the end of <i>Little Women.</i>

55:02.708 --> 55:07.625
She wanted that end-of-the-movie shot,
and I remember chatting to her about this

55:07.708 --> 55:12.458
and she was like, "I want it, I want it,
I grew up watching it, and I want it."

55:12.541 --> 55:17.208
If things have gone right, at the end,
the audience is on the edge of their seat

55:17.291 --> 55:19.291
wondering whether the good guy will win,

55:19.375 --> 55:22.500
<i>while knowing, with every</i>
<i>fiber in their being, that he will.</i>

55:24.208 --> 55:27.833
Hey, why don't you pick on someone
your own size?

55:27.916 --> 55:31.291
The morality tale
demands that the hero kills the villain.

55:35.458 --> 55:37.041
<i>The better the death,</i>

55:37.583 --> 55:41.250
the more satisfying
the vanquishing of the villain is.

55:41.333 --> 55:44.833
Someone falling from a great height
has been a classic way

55:44.916 --> 55:46.541
to finish your story.

55:46.625 --> 55:49.166
<i>Brilliantly done in </i>Die Hard,<i> of course,</i>

55:49.250 --> 55:52.875
and it gives them a moment or two
to know that they're beaten.

55:56.875 --> 55:58.958
It's a very satisfying moment
for the audience.

55:59.041 --> 56:03.875
<i>It's to enable them to feel safe.</i>
<i>You vanquish the villain so you feel safe.</i>

56:04.708 --> 56:06.166
[screaming]

56:07.583 --> 56:10.666
[Garfield] <i>And the more dastardly</i>
<i>the behavior of the villain,</i>

56:10.750 --> 56:14.916
the more karmic justice
we are praying for.

56:15.000 --> 56:19.166
There's a blood lust that a great villain
creates in an audience.

56:19.250 --> 56:21.083
Yippee-ki-yay, motherfucker.

56:27.750 --> 56:31.958
At the end of a movie, we want
to have good overcome bad.

56:32.041 --> 56:36.041
That's what drives that desire
to watch a movie with great heroes.

56:36.125 --> 56:39.500
That everything's gonna be okay
and the world's not scary.

56:40.583 --> 56:43.541
[Lowe] <i>Until the contractually</i>
<i>binding sequel brings them back,</i>

56:43.625 --> 56:46.500
<i>the last few moments of the movie</i>
<i>are for the heroes to bask</i>

56:46.583 --> 56:49.875
<i>in their hard-earned glory</i>
<i>before riding off into the distance.</i>

56:52.250 --> 56:54.458
Well, as I said at the start,
I've been Rob Lowe,

56:54.541 --> 56:57.583
and that's it
for our look at Hollywood clichés.

56:57.666 --> 57:01.083
Nothing for me to do now except
jump on my horse and/or motorcycle

57:01.166 --> 57:04.708
and ride off into the sunset
while rock music and/or hip-hop kicks in.

57:05.375 --> 57:07.041
But that would ruin my suit.

57:07.125 --> 57:11.000
So let's just abruptly roll credits
when I snap my fingers.

57:11.666 --> 57:14.666
[electronic music playing]
